      <description>&lt;p&gt;Came across this really cool short video about identities in a Sudoku square:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;iframe width=&#34;560&#34; height=&#34;315&#34; src=&#34;https://www.youtube.com/embed/pezlnN4X52g?si=uacN45qCCbdzMhka&#34; title=&#34;YouTube video player&#34; frameborder=&#34;0&#34; allow=&#34;accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share&#34; allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It is such a simple identity yet something that I had not noticed myself before.&#xA;Makes me wonder what other subset sum identities are there in a Sudoku?&#xA;Is this a linear algebra problem? Are we looking for interesting elements in the kernel of some maps?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
